Predicting the Likelihood of Being Overweight using Machine Learning Models

Ainsley Carlson

2025-10-27

1 Overview of Analysis

Using data on obesity levels based on physical condition and eating habits, I aim to predict if a respondent is overweight or not based on if they have a family member that is overweight or not. To complete this prediction I will create several different models and decide which performs the best out of all the models. The models I will be using will be a logistic regression as a reference model, a single-layer neural network, a decision tree, and an ensemble trees-BAGGING. The models will be compared across mmultiple tests and criteria to determine which model performs the best.

2 Dataset Description

The dataset used for this analysis comes from the UC Irvine Machine Learning Repository and was donated to the site on August 26, 2019. The data contains 17 attributes and 2111 records to estimate obesity levels from eating habbits and physical condition of individuals from Mexico, Colombia, and Peru. Of the 2,111 observations, 485 of which came from users through a survey available on a web platform for 30 days. The distribution of weight categories was not evenly balanced, so the rest of the data was generated synthetically using the Weka tool and SMOTE filter.

2.1 Variables

Gender [Categorical]: Gender of respondent

Age [Numerical]: Age of respondent

Height [Numerical]: Height of respondent in meters

Weight [Numerical]: Weight of respondent in kilograms

family_history_with_overweight [Binary]: Has a family member suffered or suffers from overweight?

FAVC [Binary]: Do you eat high caloric food frequently?

FCVC [Integer]: Do you usually eat vegetables in your meals?

NCP [Numerical]: How many main meals do you have daily?

CAEC [Categorical]: Do you eat any food between meals?

SMOKE [Binary]: Do you smoke?

CH2O [Numerical]: How much water do you drink daily?

SCC [Binary]: Do you monitor the calories you eat daily?

FAF [Numerical]: How often do you have physical activity?

TUE [Numerical]: How much time do you use technological devices such as cell phone, videogames, television, computer and others?

CALC [Categorical]: How often do you drink alcohol?

MTRANS [Categorical]: Which transportation do you usually use?

NObeyesdad [Categorical]: Obesity level

Looking at a summary of all the variable shows there are no missing values for the numerical or character variables. Therefore no feature engineering will be needed for the variables except for recoding the obesity level variable to be a binary variable.

4 Re-categorizing Variables as Categorical

There are several variables that are coded as numerical that represent a non-numerical response. These variable may have been coded as integers representing the non-numerical response options from the original survey respondents, but the synthetically generated responses are non-integer numerical response. For these variables I coded new character versions of the variables with the original response options based on the numerical value of the variable.

obesity_mut <- obesity %>%
  mutate(FCVC.char=ifelse(FCVC<1.5, "Never", ifelse(FCVC>=2.5, "Always", "Sometimes")),
         CH2O.char=ifelse(CH2O<1.5, "Less_than_a_liter", ifelse(CH2O>=2.5, "More_than_2L", "Between_1_and_2L")), 
         FAF.char=ifelse(FAF<0.5, "Do_Not", ifelse(FAF>=0.5 & FAF<1.5, "1_or_2_days", ifelse(FAF>=2.5, "4_or_5_days", "2_to_4_days"))), 
         TUE.char=ifelse(TUE<0.5, "0_to_2 hours", ifelse(FCVC>=1.5, "More_than_5_hours", "3_to_5_hours")), 
         NCP.char=ifelse(NCP<2.5, "Between_1_and_2", ifelse(NCP>=3.5, "More_than_3", "Three")))

obesity_mut <- obesity_mut %>%
  mutate(FCVC.char = fct_relevel(FCVC.char, "Never", "Sometimes", "Always"),
         CH2O.char = fct_relevel(CH2O.char, "Less_than_a_liter", "Between_1_and_2L", "More_than_2L"),
         FAF.char = fct_relevel(FAF.char, "Do_Not", "1_or_2_days", "2_to_4_days", "4_or_5_days"),
         TUE.char = fct_relevel(TUE.char, "0_to_2 hours", "3_to_5_hours", "More_than_5_hours"),
         NCP.char = fct_relevel(NCP.char, "Between_1_and_2", "Three", "More_than_3"),
         overweight=ifelse(NObeyesdad %in% c("Overweight_Level_I", "Overweight_Level_II", "Obesity_Type_I", "Obesity_Type_II", "Obesity_Type_III"), "Yes", "No"))

For the categorical variables graphed above, none of them appear to be evenly distributed among the responses. Very few people responded that they never eat vegetables in their meals compared to the Sometimes and Always responses. Similarly fewer people were physically active 4 or 5 days a week compared to other response, and fewer people used technological devices 3 to 5 hours a day compared to other responses for that question. Most people ate three meals a day, while few ate more than 3 meals a day. Most people tended to drink between 1 and 2 litres of water of day. It is important to remember that the data was balanced for the weight categories, so these responses do not necessarily reflect the average responses of the population.

4.1 Weight Category as a Binary Variable

For this analysis I recoded the weight category variable into a binary variable of if the respondent was overweight or not. The overweight variable is 0 if the respondents weight category if Insufficient Weight or Normal Weight, and 1 else wise.

obesity_mut %>%
  ggplot(aes( x=family_history_with_overweight, fill = overweight)) +
  geom_bar() +
  labs(title="Respondents Overweight by Family History of Being Overweight", x="Family History of Being Overweight", y="Count", fill="Overweight") +
  theme_minimal() +
   theme( axis.text.x = element_text(angle=0, vjust=.7, hjust=0.8))

The plot above shows that there are more respondents with a family history of being overweight and more respondents who are overweight. For respondents with a family history of being overweight, the majority of them are overweight themselves. Respondents who do not have a family history of being overweight appear to be more likely to not be overweight themselves.

In the fully saturated model, none of the variables seem to be highly correlated for each other, but FAVC is no longer statistically significant. Additionally, none of the technology use categories are significantly different from those who use technology less than 3 hours a day, indicating that technology usage is not a strong a predictor of being overweight. The only mode of transportation where the proportion of those who are overweight is significantly different from those who use an automobile is those who walk controlling for other variables in the model. Age, gender, weight, and height all appear to be strongly significant.

Computing the stepwise regression between the base logistic regression and the saturated logistic regression shows a model that is similar to the saturated model without the variables TUE, FCVC, or SCC. The variable TUE represents how many hours a day a person uses a technological device with the reference category being less than 3 hours a day. The variable FCVC represents how often the respondent eats vegetables within.

## predict the "success" probabilities of each model based on the entire data set
preReduced = predict(base.log, newdata = obesity_mut,type="response" )
predfullModel = predict(sat.log, newdata = obesity_mut,type="response" ) 
predforwards = predict(step.log, newdata = obesity_mut,type="response" ) 
##
prediction.reduced = preReduced

7 Decision Tree

Although height and weight were included in the logisitic regressions and single-layer neural networks I decided to remove them when making the decision trees. I found when I originally included them the decision trees only included height and weight. By only including height and weight, the decision trees were essentially going off of BMI, which was used in the original dataset to classify weight category. I made the decision to exclude them from the decision tree as the logistic regressions and single-layer neural networks cannot use height and weight to clasify obesity in the same way as the decision tree.

n = dim(obesity_mut)[1]  # sample size
# caution: using without replacement
#use 0.68 to get training dataset that is multiple of 5
train.id = sample(1:n, round(0.68*n), replace = FALSE)  
train = obesity_mut[train.id, ]    # training data
test = obesity_mut[-train.id, ]    # testing data
# arguments to pass into rpart():
# 1. data set (training /testing); 
# 2. Penalty coefficients
# 3. Impurity measure
## 
tree.builder = function(in.data, fp, fn, purity){
   tree = rpart(overweight ~ family_history_with_overweight + FAVC + FCVC.char + CH2O.char +          FAF.char + TUE.char + NCP.char + Age + Gender + SMOKE + SCC + CALC + MTRANS,                # including all features
                data = in.data, 
                na.action  = na.rpart,       # By default, deleted if the outcome is missing, 
                                             # kept if predictors are missing
                method = "class",            # Classification form factor
                model  = FALSE,
                x = FALSE,
                y = TRUE,
            parms = list( # loss matrix. Penalize false positives or negatives more heavily
                         loss = matrix(c(0, fp, fn, 0), ncol = 2, byrow = TRUE),   
                         split = purity),          # "gini" or "information"
             ## rpart algorithm options (These are defaults)
             control = rpart.control(
                        minsplit = 10,  # minimum number of observations required before split
                        minbucket= 10,  # minimum number of observations in 
                                        # any terminal node, default = minsplit/3
                        cp  = 0.01,  # complexity parameter for stopping rule, 
                                     # 0.02 -> small tree 
                       xval = 10     # number of cross-validation )
                        )
             )
  }

# function returning a sensitivity and specificity matrix
SenSpe = function(in.data, fp, fn, purity){
  cutoff = seq(0,1, length = 20)   # 20 cut-offs including 0 and 1. 
  model = tree.builder(in.data, fp, fn, purity) 
  ## Caution: decision tree returns both "success" and "failure" probabilities.
  ## We need only "success" probability to define sensitivity and specificity!!! 
  pred = predict(model, newdata = in.data, type = "prob") # two-column matrix.
  senspe.mtx = matrix(0, ncol = length(cutoff), nrow= 2, byrow = FALSE)
  for (i in 1:length(cutoff)){
  # CAUTION: "pos" and "neg" are values of the label in this data set!
  # The following line uses only "pos" probability: pred[, "pos"] !!!!
  pred.out =  ifelse(pred[,1] >= cutoff[i], 1, 0)  
  TP = sum(pred.out ==1 & in.data$overweight == 1)
  TN = sum(pred.out ==0 & in.data$overweight == 0)
  FP = sum(pred.out ==1 & in.data$overweight == 0)
  FN = sum(pred.out ==0 & in.data$overweight == 1)
  senspe.mtx[1,i] = TP/(TP + FN)
  senspe.mtx[2,i] = TN/(TN + FP)
  }
  ## A better approx of ROC, need library {pROC}
  prediction = pred[,1]
  category = in.data$overweight == 1
  ROCobj <- roc(category, prediction)
  AUC = auc(ROCobj)
  ##
  list(senspe.mtx= senspe.mtx, AUC = round(AUC,3))
}
giniROC11 = SenSpe(in.data = test, fp=1, fn=1, purity="gini")
infoROC11 = SenSpe(in.data = test, fp=1, fn=1, purity="information")

infoROC101 = SenSpe(in.data = test, fp=10, fn=1, purity="information")

Overall, the AUC scores of the models are similar enough between all the models that it varies which ones perform the best out of all them when a new training dataset is generated. It does appear consistent that the Gini and Information models are about the same for the non-penalized (1.1) and false negatives penalized (10.1) models, while they differ for the false-positives penalized (1.10) models. For this analysis, a false positive or a false negative are not necessarly worse than the other. Predicting that someone is overweight when they are not could lead to dieting and becoming underweight, which would not be healthy. However, predicting someone is not overweight when they actually are is not healthy either as they are not a normal, healthy weight. Therefore, I believe either the Gini or Information non-penalized models would be the best model to use for the decision tree.

As for which is the best model out of the logistic regression, neural network, and decision tree models, it is best to repeatedly test the AUC scores on different training data multiple and average the scores. This ensures that we are not deciding on a model that is best base on a single training dataset, especially when the AUC scores are close together. The next section of this analysis will conduct bootstrapping to determine which of these models is the best model.

8 Bootstrapping Models

8.1 Logistic Regression

##How AUCs were generated
## Do not want to include to help reduce html size
## Define an empty vector to store bootstrap AUCs.
btAUClog.vec = c()
## Select the number of bootstrap samples to be generated
B = 1000
## Size of the original sample
sample.size = dim(obesity_mut)[1]
## Vector of cut-off probabilities for construct ROC
cut.off.seq = seq(0,1, length = 100)
# bootstrap procedure starts here
for (k in 1:B){
  boot.id = sample(1:sample.size, sample.size, replace = TRUE)   # Bootstrap IDs
  boot.sample = obesity_mut[boot.id,]      # Bootstrap samples         
  ## Bootstrap logistic regression model is given below
  boot.logistic = glm(overweight~family_history_with_overweight + FAVC + CH2O.char + FAF.char + NCP.char + Age + Gender + SMOKE + CALC + MTRANS, family = binomial, data = boot.sample)
  ##
  pred.prob = predict.glm(boot.logistic, newdata = boot.sample, type = "response")
  ## vectors to store sensitivity and specificity

The biased trees have sligtly higher mean AUC scores than the non-biased trees, but they are less consistent as they have a larger 95% quantile range than the non-biased trees. Due to the larger range of AUC scores I would consider either biased tree model to be a good candidate model for predicting obesity. For the non-biased trees, the Gini model has a slightly higher mean then the Information model, but it also has a slightly wider range of values in the 95% quantile than the Information model. However, given the lower range of AUC scores for the Gini model is around 0.82, the lower values for the Gini Model would still be considered an excellent model in terms of predictability like the Information model. The main difference of why I believe the Gini model is better than the Information model is that the upper range is above 0.92, so some of the models would be considered outstanding predictors of obesity, which is not the case for the information model.

9 Summary

Overall, out of all the models tested I would rank the three best models in order the Sigmoid single-layer neural network, the adjusted logistic regression, and the non-biased Gini tree. I selected models for bootstrapping out of the ones that performed the best out of the logistic regression, single-layer neural networks, and the decision trees. These models were chosen and ranked by the mean AUC and how small their 95% quantiles were. While, the neural network model did perform the best it is important to note that it comes at the cost of a lot of computing power, so in a scenario where you need to bootstrap the model 1000 times it is not ideal unless you have high computing power that can handle computing those models. If factoring in computing power, I would say the adjusted logistic model is the best as it performed only slightly below the neural network and computes much faster. For this data, I found that the decision trees performs less consistenly the neural networks and logistic regressions so I would not reccomend them for this specific dataset.
